external_knowledge:
- A "status" in this context could indicate whether a class is active, inactive, or deprecated;
- The "created_by" column refers to the user identifier of the person who created the class;
- The "comment_count" and "version_count" provide the number of comments and versions associated with each class, respectively.

sql:
SELECT MAX(action_date) AS latest_update_date
FROM metadata_audits
WHERE action = 'updated';

external_knowledge:
- Active classes are those with a status type of 'active';
- Usage notes are additional information or annotations attached to classes;
- The earliest language alphabetically means the language code that comes first in alphabetical order, such as 'en' before 'fr'.

- "Blossomed with at least one comment" refers to classes that have at least one associated comment in the `comments` table;
- "French labels" are the human-readable labels for the classes in the French language;
- "Status types" indicate the current status of the classes (e.g., active, inactive, deprecated).

- "garden of knowledge" refers to the educational platform or system where users interact with classes;
- "most active user" is the user who has interacted with the highest number of distinct classes;
- "seed planted" represents any type of interaction (Access, Version, Comment);
- "variety of classes" refers to different class IDs.

- "user_id" refers to the identifier for the user accessing the class;
- "total access time" is the sum of all access durations for a particular class;
- "top three classes" are the classes with the highest total access times.

sql:
SELECT label_value, language, created_date
FROM labels
ORDER BY created_date DESC;

SELECT COUNT(*) AS total_accesses
FROM access_logs
WHERE class_id = 0;

external_knowledge:
- The class ID is a unique identifier for each class in the database;
- The relationship type indicates how one class is related to another (e.g., parent, child, peer);
- The creator's username is the username of the user who created the class;
- The last modified date is the date when the class was last updated.

- "blossoms" refers to classes in the database;
- "in full bloom" means the class is not deprecated (`is_deprecated = 0`);
- "praised" means having comments associated with the class (`COUNT(cm.comment_id) > 3`).

- "guardian" refers to a user who has the ability to update classes; "seeker" refers to a user who accesses classes.;
- "touched by the hand of the guardian" means the class has been updated by the guardian (user_id = 1).;
- "most recently visited by the seeker" means the class was most recently accessed by the seeker (user_id = 101).;

- 'Most recently updated' refers to the class with the latest `last_modified_date` within each `class_id`;
- 'Active classes' are those with a `status_type` of 'active';
- 'Parent or child relationship' means the class is related to another class as either a parent or a child in the `class_relationships` table;
- 'Class 1' is excluded from the results.

- Active classes are those with a status type of 'active';
- Non-deprecated classes are those with `is_deprecated` set to 0;
- English labels are those with `language` set to 'en';
- The top 10 classes are determined by the highest access counts.

- Active users are those with `is_active` set to 1;
- Deprecated classes are those with `is_deprecated` set to 1;
- Comments on deprecated classes are created by active users.

- 'Still active' refers to classes where `is_deprecated` is 0;
- 'Labeled as' refers to the `label_value` in the `labels` table;
- 'Note suggesting' refers to the `note_value` in the `usage_notes` table.

- 'Active' classes are those with a `status_id` of 0 in the `statuses` table;
- 'Frequently visited' refers to classes that have a high number of accesses in the `access_logs` table;
- 'Bear the note' means that there is at least one comment in the `comments` table with the text 'Review class usage frequently.';
